passages.text: FY25 Result - Sales- led earnings recovery underpinned by favourable housing and product cycles

Harvey Norman's strong 2H25 sales growth and July trading update was the first time it has moved ahead of JB Hi- Fi and The Good Guys on sales momentum for several years. While only one month, the outlook for Harvey Norman sales growth is robust given the low baseline and the highest leverage to an improving housing activity cycle. With the gap on sales closing in recent months, the PER multiple gap to JB Hi- Fi remains very wide (JB Hi- Fi at a \(42\%\) premium) when compared to pre- COVID levels, when JBH and HVN traded in- line on PER multiples through a number of cycles. We upgrade earnings by \(3.2\%\) in FY26 and \(9.6\%\) in FY27, and increase our price target to \(7.50\) ( \(6.50\) previously). We maintain our Overweight rating given the further cyclical uplift and product cycle tailwinds ahead.

Australian LFL sales growth now ahead of JB Hi- Fi off a low base. Following several years of lagging JB Hi- Fi, Harvey Norman has seen LFL sales growth accelerate from \(+5.3\%\) in 1H25 to \(+6.6\%\) in 2H25 and \(+6.4\%\) in July, ahead of JB Hi- Fi in July \((+7.3\%)\) in 2H25 and \(+5.1\%\) in July) and The Good Guys across both periods \((+4.0\%)\) in 2H25 and \(+3.8\%\) in July). Industry- specific tailwinds such as the Outdoor furniture replacement cycle (5 years post- COVID) and increasing uptake of AI PC products, as well as a more positive consumer spending backdrop with real wage growth and rate cuts are expected to continue driving this positive sales momentum into FY26. We forecast 1H26 LFL sales growth at \(7.0\%\) and 2H26 at \(8.0\%\) as the housing cycle continues to ramp up.

Australian margins to step up with franchisee profitability. Australian PBT margins accelerated by \(\sim 80\) bps in 2H25 as LFL sales growth accelerated to \(6.6\%\) . With a strong July trading update, we expect LFL sales momentum to continue in FY26 \((7.5\%)\) and FY27 \((6.5\%)\) . Harvey Norman's Australian franchised operations have high operating leverage due to a largely fixed cost base, as franchisee P&Ls are exposed to store wages. With good franchisee health, moderate inventory levels and further for the cycle to run, we expect Australian PBT margins to step up to \(5.9\%\) in FY26 \((+50\) bps YoY) and \(6.5\%\) in FY27 \((+60\) bps YoY).

NZ sales momentum turning, but margins yet to meaningfully expand. New Zealand has faced a particularly challenging period post- COVID as the RBNZ lifted rates to tame inflation, which drove a very subdued housing and consumer backdrop. A key theme of the reporting season was the resurgent NZ spending backdrop, with HVN seeing the clearest leverage to this, as sales improved from \(- 2.5\%\) in 1H25 to \(+4.7\%\) in 2H25 and \(+7.2\%\) in July. This coincides with \(\sim 250\) bps of RBNZ rate cuts over 12 months, which is beginning to drive a sales and earnings recovery. We expect the competitive market to weigh on the pace of margin expansion, but for earnings growth to return in Harvey Norman's largest international market.

Our Overweight rating is driven by an improving consumer outlook in Australia with real wage growth and rate cut expectations, as well as an improving consumer backdrop for NZ. We believe the share price at current levels are not accounting for aforementioned headwinds, with the valuation looking attractive at a FY26E P/E multiple of \(\sim 17x\)

The NZ market has turned a corner after several years of soft performance, driven by intense competition and muted consumer spending. NZ sales growth saw an uptick from 2H25 (LFL sales growth \(+4.7\%\) ) and July \((+7.2\%)\) , with this positive sales momentum expected to flow onto earnings from FY26.
Figure 4: NZ earnings expected to reach a positive inflection point in FY26
Source: J.P. Morgan estimates, Company data.

With the gap on sales closing in recent months, the PER multiple gap to JB Hi-Fi remains very wide (JB Hi-Fi at a \(42\%\) premium), when compared to pre- COVID levels, when JBH and HVN traded in- line on PER multiples through a number of cycles.
Source: Bloomberg Finance L.P. estimates.

- July sales momentum a forward indicator: Mgmt expects sales in July to continue through FY26 given an upbeat outlook for the consumer, given lower interest rates, housing activity, real wage growth, etc. The renovation cycle is yet to meaningfully contribute to sales growth, however we expect it to become a tailwind. A November rate cut will be important for Christmas and Boxing Day sales if it eventuates.- Computing: Seeing AI PC refresh cycle to remain strong across the 8 countries HVN operates in and has the most opportunity in FY26 and beyond.- Outdoor furniture: Expect outdoor furniture and BBQ to perform well due to the replacement and refresh cycle since COVID-19. During COVID-19 (2020-2021), outdoor furniture sales had an uptick due to lockdown rules that allowed gatherings within the home but not outside. Five years post-COVID sales uptick, a replacement and refresh cycle is expected, with outdoor furniture range now at a higher ASP (\\$8k-10k per product). Outdoor furniture as a category is becoming bigger separate to the renovation cycle.

- Middle/upper customers critical for Harvey Norman. Premium product mix has been maintained, not yet outgrowing entry level products. Harvey Norman looks at the Australian consumer through the following segments:

- Top third (house owners with no cash flow constraints) 
- Have been doing very well for some time.- Middle third (House owner, great balance sheet but CF constraints) 
- Starting to see middle third improving after third RBA cut. November cut 
- expect a strong Xmas and Boxing Day- Bottom third (Renters 
- struggling with food costs, etc.)

- The market has been competitive for some time 
- no more or less than 12 months ago in terms of promotions and discounting on the floor.- Major events 
- consumer is very aware of the events 
- HVN is very well prepared to service consumers at these events, by being well planned and executing against the plan. Responsive to competition but not seeing it get more competitive.- Harvey Norman is meeting the market on promotions.- The health of franchisees has increased in-line with franchising margins

- Cost management a focus through the organisation in FY25.- Marketing expense stepped down in Aus; marketing expense as a % of sales sitting at 4.05% globally vs. 4.8% for Australia. Comfortable with marketing spend around the world currently. The step-down is attributed to increased efficiency with marketing spend, as the brand continues to be well serviced at these levels of spending. Looking ahead, management expects marketing spend relative to sales to be maintained.
- Receivables from franchisees a proxy for inventory at franchisee level.- Comfortable with current inventory levels, so requests for accommodation were down in 2H.

- Have seen a sequential improvement in performance from 2Q25 onwards. Very competitive market- Pleased with July - a continuation of the upward trend - confident in the year ahead- PBT margin yet to pick up - should be an opportunity for margin improvement.

- Harvey Norman is performing well vs. other retailers in Ireland currently.- Considered to have market leadership in most categories in the local market.- Have another three stores that could be opened in the region.
- Finding it harder to get high-quality sites in the key region of Malaysia
Harvey Norman (Overweight; Price Target: A\(7.50)

Harvey Norman's outlook is improving off a low base as HVN progressively closes the sales gap with JB Hi- Fi and The Good Guys. Our Overweight rating is driven by an improving consumer outlook in Australia with real wage growth and rate cut expectations, as well as an improving consumer backdrop for NZ. We believe the share price at current levels are not accounting for aforementioned headwinds, with the valuation looking attractive at a FY26E P/E multiple of \(\sim 17x\) .

Our 12- month price target of \(\) 7.50\(is derived using a blended valuation of: (1) DCF (\) \ \(5.08)\) rolled forward at the cost of equity (11.3\%), less the next 12 months' dividends; (2) a sum- of- the- parts valuation (\) 8.00); and (3) a PERel valuation (\) 8.00).
